segments.text: Sir, would you state your full name and date and place of birth?
My name is Robert Burns Bossler and I was born in Saxton, a little town in Pennsylvania, on November 15, 1894.
And would you give your full name and date and place of birth?
Mary Fisher Bossler, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, June the 8th, 1891.
Thank you.
Sir, would you give us a
brief biographical statement of your early experiences and education.
Include as much as you'd like.
I was, I was graduated from the University of Pittsburgh in 1918.
I received a degree of petroleum engineer.
At that time it was a new degree and I was among the first 12 to receive that degree in the United States.
He also had the diploma sent to camp, where he was in service, and it is a cum laude degree.
It was a cum laude, and as you said, I was in the, in the May of 1918, I went into the Army Engineers, and I came out of that in December of 1918 as a second lieutenant of engineers, so it
Well the graduation services were held in June.
I was in camp and they did send the diploma to Camp Lee, but I think a lot of these incidental things are just embroidery, but not very vastly important.
But after that, after graduation, I worked in the oil industry and my experience covers a wide range of
largely in production and in a department of production called secondary recovery.

I worked in the eastern fields and in some of the western fields where the field, the particular pools were exhausted by normal production methods and we stimulated the production rate by the injection of gas or air or water and in many cases we recovered in 10-12 years
as much as they had recovered by primary production in 20 or 30 years.
So, we did right well in the production of crude oil.
My company, the last company I worked for was located in Oil City, Pennsylvania.
We had operations in and around that part of Pennsylvania, but also in West Virginia and Kentucky

and Oklahoma, some little in Texas, but not much and Kansas, and very largely in Kansas and I had a boss who was single and he was very tax conscious and he had no heirs and he wanted, except his nieces and nephews,
So he wanted to liquidate the company, which he proceeded to do in a very expert manner.
What was the name of the company?
Brundred, B-R-U-N-D-R-E-D, Brundred Oil Corporation in Oil City, Pennsylvania.
And in course of the work, I had received stock in lieu of salary increases.
During the war, they weren't allowed to increase salaries.
So to keep everybody happy, they started giving me stock in the company.
So when the liquidation occurred, I came out of it with a quite sizable bunch of stock, which was worth to me a fairly large sum of money, but it did terminate the company.
When was this?
That was in 1954.
And you had worked for them how long?
Nineteen years.
Nineteen years.

And at that time there was a position of head of the Pennsylvania Grade Crude Oil Association Research Laboratory became vacant and this was an organization set up to try to stimulate the recovery of oil from the Pennsylvania grade fields.
Those are fields located in New York, Pennsylvania, West Virginia and Eastern Ohio.
Our job was to try to find ways of increasing the recovery and this laboratory had been going on for a number of years.
This position became vacant and we moved up to Bradford on a temporary basis.
We kept our home in Oil City and took an apartment in Bradford and I was there about a year, a little over a year, and I got this call from
Mr. Whiting, and a letter from him asked me if I would come down and look at the job of teaching here at Texas A&M.
And I came down in October of 55, yeah, October of 55, and then in about December, I guess, I said yes, I would like to come and try it.
So I arrived in College Station on January 1st, 1956.
I would have arrived December 31st, but I had a grandchild born on the night of December 31st after midnight, actually the first child born in the new year.
So we stayed there till the daylight and came on down here on the 1st of January.
But I had one recollection that I certainly never will forget because
When I got in the Edge of Bryan, I called up Bob Whiting and told him where I was and he told me how to come on ahead.

We got over here to the East Gate and it was a beautiful warm day, January 1st, and he was standing there in his shirt and sleeves and he saw me coming and got the car stopped and he said, welcome to Texas.
And you could hear it for a block, you know.
It was a marvelous thing to get a welcome like that.
Did you know him from someplace before you?
No, no.
How did he learn of you?
From a Dr. Paul Torrey in Austin and Dr. George Fancher.

Dr. George Fancher was head of the department, petroleum department at Austin, the University of Texas at Austin and Paul Torrey had been active in the Pennsylvania great area and we had remained in contact through all the years and
Paul Torrey is a very strong supporter and advocate of the patrolling department of Texas A&M.

He is giving the department all of his books and all of his accumulated library and he's been a friend of the of the department for for over all time and he he told Whiting about me and George Fancher told Whiting about me and my experience and background

The position was to teach petroleum engineering economics and petroleum engineering management and my background since I had come up to, I started out as an engineer and I joined the Brunnerdorf Corporation as an engineer but by the time 1954 came around I was a member of the board, secretary of the corporation and chief engineer and a whole lot of things like that and

Having reached that level in the company, I had a great deal of experience in wheeling and dealing and accumulating land and disposing of land and made a considerable study of oil company taxation problems and in connection with the liquidation of the corporation, we had to do a great deal of groundwork
in discovering the methods that would result in the least taxation.
So that my background in these various phases made me, I say in all modesty, it made me quite well prepared for that particular area of teaching.
This was to be your first teaching experience?
Yeah, this was the first teaching experience.
Did you approach this with any apprehension?
to teaching?
Indeed I did.
They did this for me.
They had 64 seniors.
I taught seniors and I had a great regard for petroleum engineering seniors and I had in certain areas, I hadn't cracked a book in 30 years.
I, you talk about the word trepidation, I was it all over.
What, could you give me an idea of what made you decide to come to Texas, even though you had the letter and what made you decide to finally come to Texas?
Had you ever been here before?
Yeah, I had been in Texas in connection with the war, but I'd never been to Texas A&M.
I'd never been to College Station.
No, there's another factor to the matter.
John Calhoun was then, well he was the
Head of the petroleum engineering department at State College, Pennsylvania State College.
And then he came down to Texas as- You had taken some graduate work with him.
I had taken some work with John Calhoun at State College.
I see.
And he was down here, he first came down here as dean of engineering and then he moved on to something else and he's up there as a vice president now.
Yes.
But he was here.
Well I felt that I wanted to teach but I wanted to do something for the industry and this looked like a good way to do it.

The industry had been pretty darn good to me and I felt that if there was some way and this looked like a very beautiful opportunity where I could by teaching students and passing on some of my experience and background
and general philosophy that I could do a little good.
I wish you could have heard it.

Yesterday afternoon, a young fellow, we were at a wedding, and this boy was also a guest, and he came up and spoke to Bob by name and thanked him for what he had learned from him at school and told how the
various things that he had told them that they had gotten together and discussed them for two weeks.
This was a special talk I'd given to one group after I'd quit teaching.
Of course, that made us both beam.
I think so.
That's marvelous.
That's one of the big satisfactions I've had.
It's a real dividend.
I've had a couple of those.
But there aren't very many of them.
But this was completely out of blue sky.
There we were at this wedding yesterday, and the boy comes up and asked if I was Mr. Bossler.
He said his name was Garcia.
And I had made him a talk someplace, and I don't recall where it was.
But he said, we talked and we discussed what you said for two weeks after you were there.
I must have made some sort of an impression.
Could you tell me what your first impressions or recollections are of the school when you first got here, what you thought?

Well, the school was in a little bit of upheaval because of Dr. Morgan because he was advocating voluntary military and he was advocating departure from some of the quote traditions we have around here and
He was not very popular and things were a bit of an uproar, but I was not in contact.

One of the first people that Whiting took me to meet was Dr. Morgan and I was greatly impressed because he was a very pleasant and knowledgeable man and I'm sure he was quite able man judging from the jobs he's held since.
But my impressions were pretty solidly related to the department.

because I just had to buckle right down and learn and relearn and unlearn a lot of things that I had acquired over the lifetime and try to come up to date and try to do a good job and I think I did, but it took an awful awful lot of work.
I just come home from school with my head down and my feet flat on the floor from there
Midnight and the next day the same and I had to I had to get my, they gave me a month.
I came in January 1st and class started February 1st so I had a month to get my feet on the floor.
But the impression of the department is something I really feel great about and I like to tell about it because in the entire period that I was there I never heard one
member of the faculty make a derogatory remark about another one, privately or publicly or anything else.
You know in many departments in the company where I was, this was certainly not so.
There was backbiting and infighting and there was that squabbling of galore and but here at the department, honest to John, nobody ever said anything to me about another member
that they wouldn't say to their face, you know.
And it was just so, so different from what it was in the company, that it made a deep and certainly lasting impression on me.
And all the while I was there, nobody ever said anything.
And it could easily have been done, because we had some PhDs and we had some that were just BS's and I just had equivalent of a BS, and yet

If I run into a problem, some of them my mathematics were rusty as could be, I run into a problem and they were, practically everybody from whiting down would just drop what they were doing and clarify the thing for me.
The most sympathetic was Paul Crawford and Bill Hammocks.
Dan Bass was an extremely brilliant young man.
and he could make these giant strides in mathematics and I just couldn't follow, but Bill Amex, Paul Crawford would sit down and go through it step by step by step by step and show me the way.
I always appreciated that very much.
Unfortunately, Bill Amex died and Dan Bass moved out to Colorado School of Mines
Whiting was very patient and very, very good instructor.
He was just great when he would take the time to explain something.
And he gave me lots of leeway.
He said, when you're in that classroom, it's yours.
He said, don't ask me what to do.
It's your job.
I said, I'm not telling you what to do.
So we got along real good.
The books, he had the seniors prepare
At the end of the term, I overheard one man telling another that that book would be, that treatise, that subject that he had been working on, was worthy of a Ph.D.,
Oh no, it wasn't PhD work, but it was pretty good work.
We had an annual report we had to make, and I'd give them a problem on property evaluation.
I'd give them the raw data and say, what's the property worth?
We got values that varied two or three hundred percent, but it didn't worry me at all.
I said, all I want to know is whether you have the method, whether you know the procedures.

your absolute answer isn't greatly important to me, unless it's 200 million or something like that, which is utterly absurd, but they, all I was asked, and they put them up in hardback binding, you know, and they were very proud.
That passes a dissertation.
They were so valuable that some of the good ones were actually stolen by some of the people who wanted to have them in their life.
library.
They stole the Goodman.
I was kind of simple-minded.
I didn't hand them back, this is yours and this is yours and this is yours.
I put them out on the table and told them to pick theirs up and tell them what they picked up.
Picked up the Goodman's and the man who had produced the Goodman's, he came to me and said, mine's gone.
All I could leave was sorrow.
But be that as may, the department was a very closely knit, cohesive group, and I pretty much drowned in coffee the first couple of months, because Whiting would say, let's go have a cup of coffee.
Well, he was saying, well, let's go have a faculty meeting, and they'd do it over a cup of coffee, and he discussed all the faculty problems, and he'd sometimes have an agenda that long
accomplish over a cup of coffee, and I'd say, you're never going to finish that, and he said, what do you bet?
But it was very, very closely knit, cohesive group, and everybody knew what was going on because of this, and everybody had a part in what was going on, and it was a very marvelous department.
I think there's no department on the campus anywhere, anytime, ever equal to that.
You talked of...
President Morgan's problems and the upheaval.
Could you tell us whether the resentment against him was from the students or the faculty or the exes?
My understanding is it came from the exes and the board of directors.
Who were exes anyway.
Huh?
Who were probably exes anyway.
Yeah.
Many things he stood for happen now.
I didn't know many
of the students.
I didn't know very many of the faculty, but my feeling was conveyed to me in my own impressions.
There was very little trouble underneath.
It all came from above.
Ms. Bosser, could you tell us your first impressions on arriving here?
Oh my.
Yes.
The lady that came to our motel, Bob Whiting had arranged for us to stay until we found a place, came to pick me up and had a pansy that grew in her front yard in her collar.
And that made a big impression on me.
Did you find the people friendly to you?
Very friendly.
My next door neighbor

came in and I have some little old cookies and one way come in for a cup of coffee and found out that she belonged to the same church that I had belonged to as a Methodist and said that the ladies were having a meeting the next night and could I go along and I got acquainted with friends that are still good warm friends right now they uh
Very, very pleasant.
She hunted houses, and she'd go out with a real estate dealer and line up three or four, and after school I'd go out.
Uh-uh, uh-uh, uh-uh.
Finally, we came to this one.
We had been living in an apartment.
Our home was in Oil City, but it was a furnished apartment.
I had to have my cooking utensils and
dishes and bed linen and so forth.
And we just had that packed in our car.
And she found us a rented furnished apartment here that was available to people that owned it were in California.
And that was down on Gilchrist Street in North Gilchrist.
And then she was the one then that
was interested in finding a permanent home.
She knew that was temporary.
And 1st of March, by the 1st of March, we knew we were going to live here.
I think we moved in the 1st of April.
1st of March.
1st of March we moved in?
Yeah, we moved in the 1st of March.
January, February, we were hunting houses.
I came and saw this when it was occupied.
It had been built about six months before we got here, October or so, the year before, 55.
I saw this and the trees and the possibilities.
It was raw mud and no driveway, no patio, no nothing.
And the mailbox was in a tree that stood in the middle of the street out here.
The page just paved around the tree, I think.
But when we walked out of it, I said, this is what we want.
So we were very happy with everything.
Of course, there weren't as many houses available then as there are now to look at.
Oh, it was a terrible search.
Well, there were quite a few to look at, though.
And I'm still very glad that we didn't take any of the rest of them.
It's a nice place.
It's a marvelous place, and its trees are worth a fortune.
Yeah.
There were 40 trees on the lot.
And then the lot next door was unoccupied, of course.
And some people had gotten an architect to draw up plans to build a house on that.
It's comparatively a narrower lot.
I think 90 feet was all.
And that would put a driveway right up by these windows.
So we turned around, bought that lot, and later sold half of it.
So it gave us a lot more trees.
I haven't any idea now just how many trees we're doing.
The edge of the property is about 60 feet from that roof line there.
Well, the trees shade your house.
Should keep your air conditioning bill down a little bit.
That's right.
We have a smaller air conditioner than this house and the glass and so on would require because we are shaded, and it's a big asset.
Now you've talked about some of the people you were closely associated with.
Could you mention any more?
Mention the people in your department.
Well, there was Amex, Bass, and Whiting.
They had just written a book.
And then there was John Pettigo.
and Harvey Kennedy.
Harvey Kennedy was a distinguished professor who came down here from the Gulf Research Laboratory in Pittsburgh.
He was exclusively for graduate students and some seniors.
He was a very fine, very able man.
He made a lasting impression on a lot of students.
I got into the graduate student business that first spring.
I had some graduate students too.
They said that was a greater honor than being in the Sigma Psi.
That's all there was at that time.
And Dr. Kennedy and myself.
I mentioned Bass.
And then later we got Hank Ramey and he left and Joe Ossaba and then Bill McGuire came
and Doug Vaughn-Gaunton.
I had him as an undergraduate student and some graduate courses.
Now he's back with a Ph.D. teaching and he's doing very well.
Pretty much assistant to Bob Whiting, I think, in most of the things.
But that's all the people that have been in the department.
Oh, we had another
called him a schlock, S-C-H-L-A-U-D-T.
I had him as an undergraduate and then some graduate courses and he stayed on and got his Ph.D. but then he went out to work for Shell.
Apparently doing all right there.
He looked like a permanent student, you know, he was around there for about eight years or nine.
Who would you recall outside of the department?
Any other people you might have been closely associated with outside the department that you recall?
Well, yes, there's some people in the allied disciplines.
Geology, for instance.
There was Shirley Lynch, head of the department, head of the department, head of the geology department.
And Parker, Travis Parker and Clay Seward and
Horace Blank was just about to retire.
He has since retired, and I've been quite close to him ever since retirement because we have a mutual interest in the Gem and Minerals Club.
As far as his retiring is concerned, when he reached the age to retire, they...
board of directors voted an extra year for him, and then the next June, there's still another year.
Well, they couldn't after that, so when they needed him again, it was a distinguished professor for a while, but he had a hard time retiring.
Yeah, I was officially retired and went up on the stage, you know, and got the little certificate, and then
Whiting was teaching my courses and he got into a crack with some other work that he was doing and would I come back that spring of 63.
That was after your second retirement.
Spring of 63 and teach my old course again.
I actually taught an extra semester after I graduated.
After I retired.
I guess in other departments, J.G.
McGuire, his neighbor over here, and he's the associate dean of engineering now.
He was another one that I felt acquainted with.
By the way, he was a voted emeritus.
Yeah, I had an emeritus status.
What were some of the more outstanding problems and situations which confronted you or were confronted by you or by the college during your association with it?
Well, the problem confronting me was to equip myself to teach those boys and prepare an outline for the course and then accumulate the
the teaching materials and so on that I had to have for the course.
That was the outstanding problem the first year.

Of course, I rewrote the course outline and the course notebook I think about three times in the five years that I, five or six years I was teaching, but the first one was to come in from industry and start teaching and do a credible job and earn my money.
And to give the boys 60 minutes worth of time each hour, I say I was so busy doing that I had very little contact with what was going on outside of the department.
What do you regard as the more important accomplishments of A&M Beringer Association?
Oh, I would say first growth, but I think that growth should follow something else.

I think that the accomplishment that brought about the growth was the de-accenting the military and making it voluntary and the opening up the schools to the colored and opening up the schools to the women.
When we were first here,
we had a big problem.
There was some Sigma Xi owners that belonged to Sigma Xi Scientific Society or Research Society down at Prairie View.
What would we do if they came up here to a meeting because they were probably, there was just no provision for anything.
A colored man come here to sing and he couldn't stay in the MSC.
He couldn't get his hair cut here in this town.

He just had a horrible time and I certainly give old LBJ credit because one time he was scheduled to come here and he said if there's going to be any trouble with the blacks or any trouble at all, just count me out.
He said I want to see some black people there.
and that's when it opened up.
Early graduation services, you'd see two or three back rows in the back of the G. Raleigh White and that's where the few colored people sat.
That's where they stayed.
They came in and sat down.
The basketball games, they had to stay up.
In our own section.

Even a public performance like a basketball game, they had to go clear way back up there in the back and LBJ said, there'll be none of that and if you want me to come, of course it was understood that if he canceled out for some reason like that, it was going to be a lot of, a lot of fuss and feathers about why he canceled out
So, I think that his influence was largely, very largely, his influence contributed largely to the admission of colored and minority groups.
We always had Spanish, we always had Spanish, there was lots of them here, but colored, no, until about the time I was leaving here, leaving the campus.
And those things, de-accenting the military and the admission of the colored and the admission of women, I think that has resulted in the growth.
Also, I think that being a state institution and by some hook or crook, they've managed to keep fees, fees and

tuition low, so a lot of people can come here, even, even they can come, out-of-state boys can come here at less expense than they can go to their own, within their own states, and these things have resulted in attracting a lot of people here.
They, of course, the greatest, the greatest thing, of course, is the absolute magnificent influx of
minds and researchers and scholars that have been encouraged to come here.
The level of scholarship among the faculty is really great and it has been growing and been improving.
It's far and away above the level it was in 56.
Far and away above the level it was when I came here with the addition of these
these scholars, scholarly people, researchers, specialists in their line, that to my mind has been even more outstanding than the numbers.
The numbers are very gratifying, but I think the level of scholarship among the faculty, and just to see the list of the papers, it is fortnightly that passed around here.
the list of subjects that are being published and researched and the honors that are acquired by the faculty.
It's really a marvelous thing.
I don't know too much about many other faculty campuses, but certainly been a very great improvement in that area.
Do you think maybe we could, we might be carrying growth a little too far?
They're estimating 22,000 next fall.
I certainly think there's a definite limit to how big we want to be, how big we should be, and I think we're getting there pretty darn rapidly.
I couldn't see this continuous growth, 30, 40, 50,000.
That's utterly beyond
I think it should be divided up into smaller schools.
You become too machine-like, too... the pupil-professor, pupil-teacher relationships can't exist when you get too big.
I wish it would stop now.
I wish it would stop sooner.
I think it's big enough.
I think many people, I found this in
With many of the interviews I've done already, people think that we're big enough, maybe a little bigger than we ought to be.
Yeah, because the people relationship to the faculty, it just can't possibly be where there's so many people.
What do you feel were some of the greatest weaknesses or failures, lost opportunities or misdirections of the university during your association with it?

I just had nothing to say on that because as I say I had my nose to grindstone and so concerned with the departmental affairs that I had no... Would you say possibly losing Dr. Morgan might have set us back?
It did in the mind of some of us set us back.
10 or 15 years.
Well I think the things that he was advocating have now come into being
and if he had received the same support that others have since.

Rudder was a great man and he did a great many things for the university but it took him a long time, a long time to come around to some of the things that Morgan had already arrived at and if he had received the same support that Rudder received later, he probably would have moved along faster.
And what do you regard as some of the more outstanding changes that have occurred at Texas A&M?
Well, size and numbers and of course things that I've already mentioned about women and blacks and military.
Now when did you retire?
Well I officially retired in 62 and then as I say I was called back in spring of 63 to
to teach my course all over again.
You've been quite active since you did retire in doing many things.
Could you give us kind of a chronological description of your activities since you retired?
Well the first couple years we felt that we had earned some time so we did some visiting.
We went to India and Japan and the Middle East and so on and we had a son living in Canada so we

traveled a great deal over Canada and Mexico and just really traveled around a bit and then I had a little health problem in in 68 and January 69 and had an operation and about that time the Brazos County Community Council was formed actually formed in June of 68 but I didn't
become interested in it much until after I recovered a bit from my operation in the spring of 69 and it was one of these things that was well conceived.
To my mind it needed something that would keep it going, some activity, day by day activity.
I don't think you can keep a group together and just hold a monthly meeting or a quarterly meeting and talk about things and then don't do anything.
So I said we ought to have an information referral office.

I had been following one of these things in Kansas City area and knew a good deal about what they did and so on and it was apparent that there was a great many people in this area in the lower income sector and in the poverty sector that had problems
for which they couldn't provide a solution and they didn't know where to go to find a solution.
They needed a center to which they could come and describe their problems or sit, there'd be somebody to sit down with them and talk and after a while you would identify what the real problem was.
They may have said they need money but they had a problem with it but they didn't know how to manage money or that they had

too many kids and hence they always needed money or a number of reasons why they didn't have enough money but then there were problems of every sort and description and there were problems for which there were agencies already in existence

the word information and referral the referral part of it of course refers to the fact that we would refer people after we identified a problem we would refer people to the welfare the Bryan City Mission or the Salvation Army or the rehabilitation whatever it was it was set up to work on that particular problem the information was to accumulate a vast reservoir of

information regarding all of the social agencies in the area what to do and what their telephone numbers are and the people who run them and so it was to be able to make a proper referral because no use in my sending somebody to social security if it isn't a social security problem and likewise welfare or rehabilitation or anything else I had to know what these various agencies do
So I had to accumulate the information and instead of keeping it to myself, we published it as a directory of social services.
And we're working now on our fourth one, which means that we're just constantly updating these directories of social service.
Well, the main object, in a few words, the purpose of the Brazos County Community Council
occupied about that much in the Constitution.
But I can express it in a few words that the purpose of the Bradley County Community Council was to find unfilled needs in the area and do something about it.
And also look for duplication and overlap, but that was not a serious problem.
But to find the unfilled needs, well, I felt that the information referral office was an unfilled need and we did something about it.
Then there was a need for transportation among the poor people who can't get to a doctor or can't get to a hospital or can't get to groceries or can't cash their checks or anything.
So we set up a roadrunner service and since we had room in our office we said we'll try to run it and now we have a man who does nothing but
scheduled roadrunner calls and called the roadrunners, and that's all he does.
Three hours a day, five days a week.
He's also a volunteer.
He is also a volunteer.
And then we had a thing we thought was needed, but apparently it wasn't.
It was a telephone reassurance service for people who are homebound or housebound or in a wheelchair or something.
We thought it would be nice if somebody called them up every day to ask them how they were and whether they were getting along all right, whether they needed anything.
Certainly.
But we found many more people willing to do the calling than we did people who wanted to be called, so this kind of blew up.

But then we, then the summer of 62, no 72, we were asked by the Governor's Committee on Aging, that is the Bradley County Community Council was asked, if we would sponsor a thing called the Retired Senior Volunteer Program.
And we
demonstrated to them that we were capable of doing this, and they said, all right, you're it.

So now the Braddock County Community Council, considering it as a holding company or overriding company, we have one operating group, the Information Referral, and another operating group, the Road Runners, and another operating group, the RSVP.
That's what I've been doing about
Oh, 15, 20 hours a week now for about five years.
Excuse me.
Now, this might be someone needing a ride to Galveston.
Yes, maybe.
Some of my clients have.
But that's what I do, but I have a couple of other things that I'm vastly interested in.
The major one, of course, is the Junior Museum of Natural History.
This is a going thing.
I wanted it for a while, and...
have a number of exhibits over there.
We have a lot of artifacts and rocks and minerals and birds and ducks and all sorts of things, but the major thrust of the museum is education of the children in nature and science.
